					<description><![CDATA[<p>Cadence Strengthens AI Partnerships For Engineering And Robotics Cadence has expanded its AI and robotics partnerships with Nvidia. The announcement was made at its CadenceLIVE event. The company also introduced</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/cadence-ai-robotics-expansion/" data-wpel-link="internal">Cadence Expands AI And Robotic Partnerships With Nvidia And Google Cloud</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Cadence Strengthens AI Partnerships For Engineering And Robotics</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Cadence has expanded its AI and robotics partnerships with Nvidia. The announcement was made at its CadenceLIVE event. The company also introduced new integrations with Google Cloud to support advanced chip design workflows. These developments mark a significant step in how engineering teams design, test and deploy complex systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The collaboration with Nvidia focuses on combining accelerated computing with physics-based simulation systems. This alignment supports work across semiconductors, robotic systems and large-scale AI infrastructure. Nvidia describes this expanding category as physical AI, where digital intelligence interacts directly with real-world systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Cadence is connecting its multi-physics simulation tools with Nvidia CUDA-X libraries and AI models. The connection also extends into Nvidia’s Omniverse simulation environment. These tools allow engineers to study thermal and mechanical interactions in detail. The goal is to predict system behaviour before physical production begins.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The companies stated that overall system performance depends on how compute, networking and power systems interact. This requires full-system simulation rather than isolated analysis. Cadence aims to support this move toward integrated digital twin development across engineering teams.</span></p>
<h2><b>Robotics Development Advances Through AI And Physics Simulation</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Cadence and Nvidia are expanding their work on robotics development. Cadence simulation engines model how materials and forces behave in real-world environments. Nvidia contributes AI models that train robotic systems inside digital simulations. This allows robots to be trained without relying on physical testing.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Training robots in simulation reduces the need for real-world datasets. These datasets must be created with physics-accurate models. The accuracy of the simulated data directly influences the performance of trained robots. Cadence leadership noted that better physics models produce better training outcomes with fewer cycles.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Nvidia stated that leading industrial robotics companies are already using its Isaac simulation frameworks. These companies include well-established robotics manufacturers. They use Omniverse-based digital twin tools to test full production lines in software. This approach evaluates performance and safety before deployment onto physical factory floors.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The companies added that complex robot operations require high-fidelity digital environments. Simulation reduces risk and improves accuracy during design and commissioning stages. It also shortens development timelines by removing the need for manual trial-and-error in physical spaces.</span></p>
<h2><b>Cadence Introduces New AI Agent For Chip Design Automation<br />
</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_200099" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200099" class="size-full wp-image-200099" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/create-a-futuristic-neon-lit-scene-of-an_t3GAQYF_Sx-4RRaZ5ifwHQ_t5mHyAZ9R-6fdYm70EMGEw_cover.png" alt="AI system converting circuit designs into silicon chip layouts with automated workflows and cloud-based processing." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-200099" class="wp-caption-text">Cadence’s AI-powered chip design agent accelerates layout generation and verification through intelligent automation and cloud integration. Source: Created by Ventureburn</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Cadence also introduced a new AI agent for chip design automation. The system focuses on physical layout tasks in later stages of </span><a href="https://www.silicondevelopment.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">silicon development</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. It translates circuit designs into physical chip layouts. This work builds on an earlier agent released for front-end design tasks. That earlier agent interprets circuit descriptions. The new agent completes the translation into silicon-ready layouts.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The system will be available through Google Cloud. Cadence is integrating its electronic design automation tools with Google’s AI models. The integration supports automated design and verification workflows. It also allows teams to run workloads in the cloud rather than on costly local hardware.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Cadence described its ChipStack AI Super Agent as a system that applies reasoning across different chip design stages. It uses model-based coordination to interpret design intent and execute required tasks. Early deployments show up to ten times productivity improvement across design and verification work.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company did not disclose customer names in these deployments. However, it stated that the benefits span multiple design functions. These include layout generation, verification cycles and automated analysis tasks. The system aims to reduce workflow bottlenecks by coordinating design stages through structured AI reasoning.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/wealth-com-raises-65m-ai-wealth-platform/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Wealth.com Raises $65 Million to Expand AI Wealth Planning Platform</span></a></p>
<h2><b>Digital Twins Support Large-Scale AI Factories And Data Centres</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Cadence and Nvidia also highlighted new work on large-scale digital twin systems. These tools help engineers simulate data centre infrastructure before building physical environments. The companies stated that trial-and-error testing is too costly for modern AI infrastructure. Simulation reduces risk and improves performance planning.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The collaboration integrates Cadence system analysis tools with Nvidia frameworks. Engineers can model power systems, cooling methods and airflow patterns. This allows them to explore different design configurations safely. A 10-megawatt AI factory example showed that small power adjustments can produce major efficiency gains.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The companies said digital twins reveal how IT load, cooling systems and airflow interact. Understanding these relationships helps operators increase efficiency while staying within safety limits. It also reduces delays during deployment. Engineers can adjust designs in software before building physical systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Cadence stated that its simulation tools allow teams to test designs at full scale. They help identify thermal issues, power constraints and performance bottlenecks. This supports more confident deployment across complex engineering projects. Nvidia also noted that AI is becoming essential for quantum computing reliability.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To stay updated on crypto venture capital funding and market trends, visit our </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/category/news/venture-capital/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">venture capital news section</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> for more insights.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/cadence-ai-robotics-expansion/" data-wpel-link="internal">Cadence Expands AI And Robotic Partnerships With Nvidia And Google Cloud</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
